Hi Stephen,   
thanks a lot for your useful article. However, I have some doubts about my implementation, which I copied below. I'm starting from an existing class MyController, which is handling HTTP requests. I tried to make the class asynchronous by wrapping the synchronous code with Task.Run.   
What do you think, is the usage of Task.Run in this case correct and am I using it in a proper way at all?   
Thanks a lot in advance. :)  
P.S.: Don't know why, the site is adding stuff: 'myresponsedto="" ' should be simply myresponsedto

public class MyController  
{  
 public virtual async Task<ihttpactionresult> PostAsync([FromBody] MyRequestDto objDto)  
 {  
 var response = await Task.Run(() =>_myHandler.Execute(objDto));  
 return Ok(response);  
 }  
}

public class MyHandler : IHandler<myrequestdto, myresponsedto="">  
{  
 public MyResponseDto Execute(MyRequestDto requestDto)  
 {  
 MyResponseDto responseDto = Router.Call(requestDto);  
 return responseDto;  
 }  
}

public class Router<myrequestdto, myresponsedto="">  
{  
 private System.Net.Http.HttpClient _httpClient;

 public void Initialize()  
 {  
 _httpClient = new System.Net.Http.HttpClient();  
 }

 public MyResponseDto Call(MyRequestDto requestDTO)  
 {  
 var myResponse = _httpClient.SendAsync(myRequest).Result;  
 return Map<myresponsedto>(myResponse);  
 }  
}

No, you shouldn't be using Task.Run nor Result on ASP.NET.

Instead, just let the asynchronous nature of the code flow up:

class Router {  
async Task<myresponsedto> CallAsync(MyRequestDto requestDto) => Map<myresponsedto>(await _httpClient.SendAsync(requestDto));  
}

class MyHandler {  
Task<myresponsedto> ExecuteAsync(MyRequestDto requestDto) => Router.CallAsync(requestDto);  
}

class MyController {  
async Task<ihttpactionresult> PostAsync([FromBody] MyRequestDto objDto)  
{  
var response = await _myHandler.ExecuteAsync(objDto);  
return Ok(response);  
}  
}

